        <!--Project Intro-->
        <div class="intro">
            <h2>A weekly-output-based design challenge</h2>
            <p>My social life revolves largely around dining out.<br><br>My love affair with food makes me all the more wary of the quality of the current social dining experience, from discovering about new restaurants to sharing our dining experience with others after.</p><br><br>
        </div>

        <!--Project Summary-->
        <div id="project-summary">
            <br><h4><strong>ABOUT</strong><br>
                My first dive into a mobile app redesign
                <strong>Duration:</strong> February-May 2018<br>
                <strong>Role:</strong> Product Designer, User Researcher<br>
                <strong>For:</strong> People who love to share meals out with friends, family, and colleagues<br><br>

                <strong>SKILLS USED</strong><br>
                User Research<br>
                Journey Mapping<br>
                Flowcharting and diagramming<br>
                Wireframing (using Sketch)<br>
                <a href="#prototype-opentable" class="blue">Prototyping (using InVision)</a></h4>
            </div>
    </div>

    <!--Project Content-->
    <h2><strong>Observations</strong></h2>
    If there is one thing that I <p class="highlight-open-table">dread </p>about dining out with friends or colleagues, it would be <p class="highlight-open-table">the amount of time and effort spent taking care of the latter part of the dining experience‚Äì</p>requesting for the check during peak hours, devising a plan for splitting the total bill, and enduring the back-and-forth with the staff about payment policies and processing restrictions, to mention a few.<br><br>
  Do New Yorkers get a similar feeling of dread for this reason?<br><br>

    <h2><strong>User Research</strong></h2>
    With the <p class="highlight-open-table">time constraint</p>, I conducted a remote survey to learn more about the collective dining experiences of 10 people ages 18‚Äì24 currently living in New York.<br>
    <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-opentable/survey.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="I conducted a survey about dining out in New York via Google Forms"><br>

  <h5><strong>1. Dining-out Frequency</strong></h5>
  The sample comprises <p class="highlight-open-table">frequent diners‚Äì with 90% of the pool eating 2 to 5 times a week, on average.</p>

    <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-opentable/frequency.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="A chart showing sample's dining frequency">

    <p class="highlight-open-table">9 out of 10</p> frequently dine out with friends or colleagues.
    <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-opentable/frequency-2.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="A chart showing how often the sample dines out with friends or colleagues">
    <h3 class="image-caption"><em>NOTE 5 for Frequently and 1 for Rarely</em></h3><br><br>

    <h5><strong>2. Preferred Payment Method</strong></h5>
    <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-opentable/payment.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="A chart showing how the sample prefers to to split the check">
    ‚Ä¢  <p class="highlight-open-table"> 7 out of 10 prefer splitting the total check according to individual and/or shared orders.</p> 1 of the 7 selected ‚ÄúWe don‚Äôt split the check. It‚Äôs my or someone else‚Äôs treat!‚Äù<br><br>

    ‚Ä¢  <p class="highlight-open-table">2 out of 10 prefer splitting the total check evenly.</p><br><br>

    ‚Ä¢  1 of them described how <em>‚ÄúOne person puts down a single card to make it easy for the waiter. Then we Venmo each other for our portions later.‚Äù</em><br><br>

  Additionally, all of them <p class="highlight-open-table">prefer credit/debit cards to cash as method of payment.</p><br><br>

    <h5><strong>3. Making Reservations</strong></h5>
    <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-opentable/reserve.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="A chart showing how the sample makes table reservations">
    <p class="highlight-open-table">Overall, OpenTable was the most popular booking tool</p> (Other choices: Resy, Yelp, making phone calls, through restaurant‚Äôs website, physically inquiring)<br><br>

    <h5><strong>4. "How can your dining experience be improved?‚Äù</strong></h5>
    <em>‚ÄúSettling payments to the restaurant <p class="highlight-open-table"> through an application‚Äù</p><br><br>

    <p class="highlight-open-table">‚ÄúAutomatic bill-splitting‚Äù</p><br><br>

    ‚ÄúHaving machines/iPads for menus so <p class="highlight-open-table">ordering process can be streamlined & staff interaction will be lessened‚Äù</p><br><br>

    ‚ÄúMore <p class="highlight-open-table">automation</p>, less waiting‚Äù<br><br>

    ‚ÄúI wish restaurants had <p class="highlight-open-table">POS systems</p> that rang in orders by person instead of by table and then could easily print and <p class="highlight-open-table">charge on a per person basis instead of splitting up an itemized bill by hand</p> because I know that is time consuming/hard for server.‚Äù<br><br>

        ‚Äú<p class="highlight-open-table">If the check can be separated from the beginning instead</p>, so we don‚Äôt have to try to tell the waiter who got what and so forth.‚Äù</em><br><br><br>



  <h2><strong>User and User Goals</strong></h2>
  <h5 class="highlight-open-table">A student or young professional</h5> wants to:<br><br>
  ‚Ä¢ know the current capacity of a restaurant<br>
  ‚Ä¢ book a reservation and invite his/her friends<br>
  ‚Ä¢ select items from the menu<br>
  ‚Ä¢ split the total bill‚Äì <h5 class="highlight-open-table">all through a single app!</h5><br><br><br>


  <h2><strong>User Journey Maps</strong></h2>
    <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-opentable/indira_journey.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="Indira's user journey">
    <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-opentable/omar_journey.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="Omar's user journey">
    <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-opentable/taylor_journey.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="Taylor's user journey">

  <h2><strong>Key Insights</strong></h2>
  ‚Ä¢ Most diners access booking tools and coordinate plans on their <p class="highlight-open-table">mobile devices.</p><br><br>
  ‚Ä¢ Users become <p class="highlight-open-table">anxious</p> when dining in a group especially if they have a tight budget or are avoiding an overdraft.<br><br>
  ‚Ä¢ Not all bill splitting methods (split evenly, per individual and shared orders, etc) can be done by the establishments.<br><br>
  ‚Ä¢ The <p class="highlight-open-table">disconnect between the staff and diners</p>, especially in notifying diners of acceptable payment and splitting methods and the act of bill splitting itself, <p class="highlight-open-table">ruins the dining experience for many.</p><br><br><br><br>


  <h2><strong><em>How might we streamline the social smart-dining experience?</em></strong></h2>

    <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-opentable/flowchart_v2.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="Mapping out the ideal overall dining experience with the app">
  Upon laying out the user experience flow, I noticed that high-level features (such as making a reservation, discover/search, confirming attendance, payments, etc) have already been implemented and nearly perfected by apps‚Äì mainly by OpenTable.
  <br><br>

  This <p class="highlight-open-table">marked up version</p> identifies components already made available in the OpenTable mobile app:

    <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-opentable/ot_flowchart_v2.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="Red dots mark the steps already made available in the OpenTable mobile app">

    <h2><strong>Rethinking My Approach</strong></h2>
    <h5>My initial plan of designing and building a booking app from scratch no longer seemed feasible.</h5>

    1. Many diners already use OpenTable. The <p class="highlight-open-table">high effort and time-based switching costs</p> will discourage users from switching to a new booking tool.<br><br>

    2. Another option would be to create an app purely for custom bill splitting; however, the <p class="highlight-open-table">back and forth between booking apps and services</p> is tedious and <p class="highlight-open-table">counterintuitive</p>. This creates a disjointed experience.<br><br>

  Since a large pool of millennial diners in New York are already on OpenTable, I chose to <p class="highlight-open-table">redesign</p> the existing experience to accommodate (1) a walk-in option (and access to waitlist) via geolocation, (2) an interactive in-app menu, and (3) an option for customized bill splitting.<br><br>

  <h2><strong>OpenTable Tab</strong></h2>

  During my trip to LA, I found out about OpenTable‚Äôs Tab, an in-app feature that eliminates the back-and-forth of cash or credit cards between the staff and the diner/s.

  <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-opentable/app.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="OpenTable's Tab feature">

  Although Tab offers the convenience of paying through phone, <p class="highlight-open-table">it still does not enable bill splitting.</p> For this reason, I pursued designing the bill splitting feature for Tab.<br><br>

  <img src="<%= image_path("images/project-opentable/web-app.png") %>" class="zoomImages" alt="Only two restaurants on OpenTable Tab in the whole of New York.">

  Tab was piloted in June 2016, but <p class="highlight-open-table">there are only two restaurants in New York that are actually on OpenTable Tab</p>‚Äì Big Daddy‚Äôs and Duke‚Äôs.<br><br>

  It‚Äôs been almost two years since the Priceline Group (PCLN) piloted OpenTable Tab. This made me question‚Äì<br>

  <h5><em>Why there aren‚Äôt more restaurants utilizing Tab for rapid turnover, increased security and trust, and a decrease in customer complaints that emerge from traditional payment processes?</em></h5>

  I looked to OpenTable‚Äôs interface to find the reason/s for Tab's low market penetration.<br><br><br>

    <h2><strong>Sketching New Touchpoints</strong></h2>

    <h3 class="image-caption"><em>All sketches and designs are based on the OpenTable app‚Äôs version (Ver.11.11.0) as of March 1, 2018.</em></h3><br><br>

  I started sketching screens from the splash page and through the check-in touchpoint. Linking existing screens with new ‚Äúsolution screens‚Äù helped me explore the feasibility and efficiency of the solutions envisioned.<br><br>

